// Regression: tinyc's preprocessor only treated `\\\n` (backslash + LF) as a
// line continuation. Source files checked out on Windows with the default
// `core.autocrlf=true` end up with `\r\n` line endings, so a macro like
//
//     #define FOO(x) \\\r\n
//         do_something(x)
//
// reached the preprocessor as `\\\r\n` and the line-continuation check at
// preprocess.c:221 failed (it required the byte after `\` to be exactly
// `\n`, not `\r`). The backslash then fell through to the token loop as an
// unexpected character, producing
//
//     tinyc lex error at line <N>: unexpected '\\'
//     tinyc parse error at line <N+1>: expected return type
//
// on the macOS/Linux clones of any header that defined a multi-line macro
// (e.g. corec/base/io.h's `println`). The Windows CI selfhost step
// (build_tinyc_wasm.sh → wasmtime + tinyc.wasm on Windows-checked-out
// sources) failed at the very first source file because of this.
//
// The MRE embeds CRLF line endings literally in a multi-line macro so the
// preprocessor MUST accept `\\\r\n` to compile the program at all. With
// the bug, compilation fails before main runs; with the fix the macro
// expands cleanly and main prints 7.

#define ADD3(a, b, c) \
    (a) + \
    (b) + \
    (c)

int main() {
    int x = ADD3(1, 2, 4);
    _tinyc_print(x);
    return 0;
}
